this went in a few directions bc its mostly just me being happy about how the kids talked about this stuff and that I could do this with them. I'm proud of them
I don't want to hear kids are "too young" to talk to openly and honestly! they get it! they're people! talk to them!!!!!

"I'm feeling sad!" a girl said. "why are you sad?" I asked. "I miss my mom" she said. she is 4 and her mom is a single mom. her father died. her mom works long hours to pay for school. we talked about feeling sad and feeling love. she felt better. 5/

another girl said "yeah some people have different skin and some people are tall". they talked about found families, biracial families, gay parents, single parents. and they all loved it. we talked about feelings and they were eager to tell me how they feel 4/

I told them they were right and all families look a little different. one girl started talking about discrimination. all these kids are ages 3-6. she said "some people don't have homes and some people don't have money and some people don't have food but they love each other" 3/

most of them gave me the same kind of answer: "family is where you all love each other and spend time together". I only had one child say family lives together. and none of them mentioned "a mom and a dad" unless it was them describing their own family 2/

I've been talking about relationships and family this month to the kids bc of valentines day (and we have a family who don't celebrate it so I wanted to avoid focusing on that). yesterday I asked the circle "what is a family" 1/
